-- South African Stocks Climb, Led by Anglo American, BHP Billiton, Richemont
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-12-21T11:17:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-21/south-african-stocks-advance-in-opening-trading-led-by-anglo-bhp-sasol.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose for the second day, climbing 216.39, or 0.7
percent, to 31,948.91 at 1:09 p.m. in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, increased to the highest in a month, gaining 5.63 rand,
or 1.7 percent, to 339.48 rand. Copper rose 1.2 percent to
$9,310 a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange. Lead, nickel
and aluminum also increased.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, strengthened for the second day, rising 3.17 rand, or
1.2 percent, to 270.26 rand, the highest in a week.  Cie Financiere Richemont SA  (CFR SJ), the Swiss luxury
goods and watch-maker, rose for the second day in three, adding
68 cents, or 1.7 percent, to 39.78 rand. Swiss watch exports
increased 30 percent, to 1.77 billion Swiss francs ($1.8
billion), according to statistics released by the Federation of
the Swiss Watch Industry.  Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, increased for the second day, gaining 1.34 rand,
or 0.4 percent, to 335.05 rand. Oil climbed for the third day,
gaining as much as 1.1 percent to $89.77 a barrel.  White Water Resources Ltd.  (WWR SJ), a mining investment
company, fell 2 cents, or 6.1 percent, to 31 cents. A close at
this level would be the lowest since Dec. 8. The company said it
expected to report a loss per share of less than 1 cent in the
first half through September, compared with earnings per share
of 0.83 cents the same period a year earlier.  To contact the reporter on this story:
